column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE BRIDGESTONE APM COMPANY FACILITY AT 245 COMMERCE WAY IN UPPER SANDUSKY, OHIO, FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE END OF THE UNLOADING LINE OF THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO.,  INC.  TANK TRAILER. BRIDGESTONE APM COMPANY PERSONNEL SUPPLIED A BUCKET CONTAINING NEUTRALIZER TO CATCH THE FREE PRODUCT.  NO FREE PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND SURFACE. APPROXIMATELY TWO CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED INTO THE BUCKET.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE FITTING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE INTERNAL/EXTERNAL VALVE ON THE UNLOADING LINE.  THE SMALL QUANTITY OF PRODUCT REMAINING AT THE END OF THE LINE WAS ALLOWED TO DRAIN INTO THE BUCKET, WHICH WILL BE HELD BY BRIDGESTONE APM COMPANY FOR DISPOSITION.  THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. TANK TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THEIR SARDIS, OHIO TERMINAL FOR REPAIRS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Tank trailer, semi-trailer or full trailer (two axles)

column168: A CLOSED BULK BIN CONTAINING FLAMMABLE SOLID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON-SITE AND THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED AS A PRECAUTION.  THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS DETERMINED TO BE WATER FROM THE FLAMMABLE SOLID BEING SHIPPED WET.  THE DRIVER APPLIED PLASTIC OVER WATER TO PROVIDE INITIAL CONTAINMENT AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE CONSIGNEE ARRIVED ON-SITE TO REMOVE THE SPILLED WATER AND PLASTIC.  THE PLASTIC WAS PLACED INTO A DRUM AND TRANSPORTED TO THE US LIQUIDS FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL.  THE BULK BIN CONTINUED ON TO CONSIGNEE.  THE CARRIER WILL RECOMMEND TO SHIPPER THE INCOMPATIBILITY OF PLACING LIQUID IN CONTAINERS DESIGNATED FOR SOLIDS.

A CLOSED BOX BIN CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING A LIQUID AT THE WEIGH STATION.  A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO ASSESS THE INCIDENT AND PROVIDE CLEANUP ACTIONS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BOX BIN CONTAINED A SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTAINERS, IN 1 GALLON OR LESS CAPACITY, HOLDING LIQUID IN ADDITION TO THE HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID AS DESCRIBED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.  THE MOST EFFECTIVE MEANS TO MITIGATE THE INCIDENT WAS TO PATCH AREAS IN THE REAR OF CLOSED BULK BIN WHERE SLIGHT PINHOLES WERE DETECTED.  THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED AND CARRIER CONTINUED ON TO CONSIGNEE.  CARRIER WILL RECOMMEND TO SHIPPER TO PROPERLY CHARACTERIZE HAZARDOUS WASTE AND CONFIRM COMPATIBILITY PACKAGING.

column168: PORTABLE TANK LOADED ON A VAN TRAILER RELEASED APPROX. 4000 LBS. OF WASTE NITRIC ACID.  THE TRAILER WAS PARKED AT LOADING DOCK ON SATURDAY MORNING FOR OFFLOADING MONDAY.  INVESTIGATION LED TO ONE OF THESE POSSIBLE CAUSES OF THE RELEASE: (1) VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED WHEN FILLED, (2) VALVE VIBRATED OPEN DURING TRANSPORTATION OR (3) VALVE WAS STRUCK DURING LOADING BY LOADING EQUIPMENT.  THE OUTLET VALVE CAP HELD CONTENTS UNTIL GASKET FAILED.  THE RELEASE WAS MITIGATED BY NEUTRALIZING THE ACID WITH SODIUM CARBONATE AND THEN RINSED WITH WATER.  NEUTRALIZED ACID AND RINSATE WERE RECOVERED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  SHIPPING FACILITY TO RECEIVE RE-TRAINING ON TANK VALVE SECURITY AND INSPECTION.

column168: DURING THE LOADING PROCESS OF OUR BULK TRUCK WITH METHYL AMYL KETONE, ONE COMPARTMENT VALVE WAS MISTAKENLY LEFT IN THE OPEN POSITION.  THE PERSONA LOADING THE TRUCK WASN'T IN A POSITION THAT HE COULD IMMEDIATELY SEE THAT THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLING ONTO THE CONCRETE BELOW THE TRAILER.  UPON NOTICING WHAT WAS HAPPENING, HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP USED TO MOVE THE MATERIAL TO THE TRAILER, PROCEEDED TO THE TRAILER VALVE AND SHUT IT AND SUMMONED OTHER PLANT PERSONNEL IN THE AREA TO HELP STOP THE FLOW OF MATERIAL ON THE GROUND WITH FLOOR DRY MATERIAL.  A DIKE WAS BUILT AROUND THE MATERIAL AND THE FLOOR DRY WAS THEN PLACED ON THE REMAINING MATERIAL AND ABSORBED.  THIS FLOOR DRY  MATERIAL WAS THEN COLLECTED INTO DRUMS AND WILL BE SHIPPED OFF-SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE PERSON LOADING THE TRUCK SIMPLY DIDN'T CHECK THE VALVE BEFORE LOADING, WHICH IS OUR STANDARD PRACTICE.  THIS WORK INSTRUCTION WAS REVIEWED WITH THE PERSON INVOLVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON COUNTY ROAD 26 WEST IN HAYNEVILLE, ALABAMA, THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, INC. VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE MONTGOMERY ALABAMA FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MONTGOMERY POLICE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE MONTGOMERY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ABLE TO STOP THE RELEASE BY TURNING THE TWO, TWO INCH CAPS ON THE CARGO TANKER WHERE THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM.   THE MONTGOMERY FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO PLACED DOWN ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF MOBILE, ALABAMA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  SLAY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, INC. PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TANKER INTO A NEW CARGO TANKER, WHILE SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES MONITORED THE TRANSFER PROCESS.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES USED A NEUTRALIZER TO NEUTRALIZE THE FREE PRODUCT, TO CONTAIN AND REMOVE IT FROM THE AFFECTED SURFACE.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES PLACED ALL PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ALL THE NEUTRALIZED FREE PRODUCT INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE THREE CORNERS LANDFILL FACILITY IN PIEDMONT, ALABAMA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WAS ONE FATALITY, THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, INC. DRIVER, AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: OUR TRAILER #113 WAS LOADED AT RHODIA WITH SULFURIC ACID.  THE VENT VALVE WAS NOT CHECKED AND REMAINED OPEN WHEN WE LEFT RHODIA'S FACILITY.  WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED BY RHODIA THE VENT HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN, THEY NOTIFIED US AND WE CONTACTED OUR DRIVER.  HE HAD ALREADY REACHED THE DELIVERY POINT AND HAD UNLOADED THE MATERIAL.  WE HAD POLAR SERVICE CENTER MAKE MODIFICATIONS TO PREVENT THIS FROM RE-OCCURRING AND ADDED ADDITIONAL SIGNAGE TO KEEP AWARENESS AT THE FOREFRONT.  WE HAVE ALSO AMENDED OUR TRAILER INSPECTION FORM TO ASSURE EVERY VALVE IS CLOSED & SECURED BEFORE LEAVING OUR FACILITY OR A DISTRIBUTOR FACILITY.

UPON OPENING THE TRAILER, STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  AFTER INVESTIGATING, 1 PAIL WAS NOTICED LAYING ON ITS SIDE BETWEEN 2 PALLETS.  PAIL WAS NOTICED TO HAVE SMALL LEAK, LEAKING ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  PAIL WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND PLACED IN THE YARD TO STOP FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE APPROXIMATE 1 GALLON WAS ABSORBED INTO THE WOOD TRAILER FLOOR AND EVAPORATED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE PAIL BEING CRUSHED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, A SHOVEL AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THIS IS THE ONLY FREIGHT IN THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: GATX 54878 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT AT 9:15AM ON SEPTEMBER 11, 2003, IN THE LOCK HAVEN YARD OF THE NITTANY & BALD EAGLE RR. CONDUCTOR ON THE LOCK HAVEN YARD CREW MADE THE DISCOVERY. CAR OWNER GATX WAS NOTIFIED AND LOCAL RAILROAD PERSONNEL SET UP A CONTAINMENT UNIT. GATX DISPATCHED A MINI-MOBILE UNIT FROM SHOP 182 IN MASSBURY, OHIO. THIS UNIT ARRIVE AT 1:45PM ON SEPTEMBER 11, 2003. GATX PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN BOTTOM VALVE MOUNTING PLATE BUT THE EFFORT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. GATX THE NOTIFIED BASC CORP., THE CAR LESSER, AND BASF DISPATCHED HMHTTC RESPONSE, INC. TO TRANSLOAD CONTENTS OF RAIL CAR INTO TANKER TRUCKS. HMHTTC FIRST RESPONDED ARRIVE ON SCENE AT 8:20PM, SEPTEMBER 11, 2003. FIRST TRANSLOAD TRUCK ARRIVED AT 10:00PM SAME DATE. FIVE TRUCK LOADS WERE REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR, WHICH WAS THEN DETERMINED TO BE EMPTY. LAST TRUCK LOAD OF PRODUCT REMOVED FROM CAR AT 1:50PM, SEPTEMBER 12, 2003. HMHTTC THEN READIED CAR TO MOVE TO A HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS. HMHTTC COMPLETED THAT TASK AND DEPARTED AT 4:10PM, SEPTEMBER 12, 2003. A ONE-WAY WAIVER (FRA 0309206) WAS OBTAINED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED IN HOME SHOP STATUS. CAR DEPARTED ON NITTANY & BALD EAGLE RR AT LOCK HAVEN, PA., VIA NORFOLK SOUTHERN RY FOR HOME SHOP REPAIRS ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2003.

TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP.  THERE WERE SEVERAL DRUMS LEAKING.  THE MAIN LEAK CAME FROM A NON-HAZARDOUS PRODUCT CALLED MAKON NF-12.  VERY SMALL AMOUNTS (A FEW OUNCES) LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUMS CONTAINING POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE AND MAYQUEST 1500 (1 HYDROXYEYTHLENE).  THESE DRUMS LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THEIR BUNGS DUE TO THE CARGO SHIFTING FORWARD DURING TRANSPORT.  SINCE THEY WERE PLASTIC DRUMS, PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THEM VIA OTHER DRUMS AND A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE BUNG AT THIS TIME.  THE DRUMS WERE WIPED DOWN AND RE-LOADED ONTO THE CONTAINER.  CLIFF BERRY INC. CLEANED THE SPILL.

DRIVER HAD BEEN IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING FOR QUITE SOME TIME WHEN HE CHECKED WITH THE PLANT OPERATOR, HE WAS ADVISED TO GO BACK TO HIS UNIT AND THEY (PLANT) WOULD INCREASE THE AIR PRESSURE FOR THE UNLOADING UP FROM 8 PSI TO 12 PSI.  AS THE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETING, THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE VENT ON THE PLANT'S STORAGE TANK. ABOUT 20 GALLON OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID SPILLED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE STORAGE TANK.  SPILLAGE WAS COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF BY CONSIGNEE. THE GAUGE ON THE CUSTOMER TANK SHOWED 4,000 GALS.  WHEN IN FACT THE TANK HAD 12,000 GALS IN THE TANK.  THE PLANT OPERATOR SIGNED THE PAPERWORK GIVEN THE CTL DRIVER THE AUTHORITY TO UNLOAD AND WHILE UNLOADING THE CUSTOMERS TANK OVERFLOWED INTO THE CUSTOMERS CONTAINMENT AREA.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CUSTOMER GAUGE MALFUNCTIONED.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE TANK OVERFLOWING.  THE CUSTOMER CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT IN THEIR CONTAINMENT AREA.

THE DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD THE UNIT WITH 98% SULFURIC ACID.  THE DRIVER FINISHED LOADING AND PROCEEDED TO THE SCALES INSIDE THE PLANT FACILITY WHEN ONE OF THE PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED SOMETHING LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SEAL IN THE INTERNAL VALVE HAD STARTED TO LEAK.  CTL SENT A TRAILER MECHANIC OUT TO MAKE THE REQUIRED REPAIRS TO THE VALVE.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED OF PROPER INSPECTION OF A CARGO TANK PRIOR TO AND AFTER LOADING A CARGO TANK AND THE IMPORTANCE OF THESE INSPECTION PRIOR TO MOVING THE UNIT FROM THE LOADING AREA.  THE DRIVER RECEIVED A WRITTEN CORRECTIVE ACTION AND WAS PUT ON A 90 PROBATION PERIOD.

DRIVER WAS LOADING TRAILER AT LEASE SITE AND OVERFILLED TRAILER DUE TO NOT FOLLOWING ESTABLISHED LOADING PROCEDURES. SUPERVISION WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND CLEANUP EFFORTS WERE STARTED. IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING ESTABLISHED LOADING PROCEDURES WAS RE-EMPHASIZED WITH DRIVER. DISCIPLINARY ACTION AS APPROPRIATE.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AS A RESULT OF A NOTICEABLE ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER CLOSURE AREA HAD FAILED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS LATER CONTACTED REGARDING DISPOSITION.

THIS STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AS A RESULT OF THE SHIPMENT BEING DROPPED AND THE CHIME AREA BEING COMPROMISED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION WITH SHIPPER IN REGARD TO DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE PROBLEM WAS DISCOVERED.   HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM ONE OF THE BOXES IN THE SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A METAL CYLINDER.  APPARENTLY THE VALVE STEM WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF GAS INTO THE PACKAGE. THE CYLINDER RELEASED ITS TOTAL CONTENTS INTO THE PACKAGE AND SUBSEQUENTLY DISSAPATED.  THE ITEM WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.
A COUPLE OF LEAKS ON THIS LOAD.  1ST DAY HAD A LEAKY PVC PIPE, ALSO HAD A HOSE DAMAGED HOLE IN IT AND THE NEXT ATTEMPT THE PVC PIPE SPRUNG ANOTHER LEAK.  WIPED UP WITH SPILL PADS.
CUSTOMER HAD A PVC PIPE CONNECTION LEADING TO THEIR STORAGE TANK AND IT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT.  SHUT DOWN & SOMEONE FIXED IT.  USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN IT UP.

column168: SHOLOM CHAPEL MORTUARY SHIPPED HUMAN REMAINS IN A WOODEN CASKET WHICH WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED.  WHEN THE CASKET WAS OFF LOADED, BODILY FLUIDS SEAPED OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE CASKET.  IN TRYING TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS SEAPING OUT OF THE CASKET,WE LEARNED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD PACKED THE HUMAN REMAINS IN 10 LBS OF DRY ICE.  THE SHIPPER NEVER DISCLOSED TO AMERICAN THAT THE CASKET CONTAINED DRY ICE.  NOR DID THE SHIPPER PREPARE THE NECESSARY DOCUMENTATION TO TRANSPORT THIS HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AMERICAN AIRLINES SUSPENDED ACCEPTANCE OF SHIPMENTS FROM SHOLOM MORTUARY AND WILL NO LONGER DO BUSINESS WITH  THEM.

EMPLOYEES AT RAIL YARD OBSERVED WHITE VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 62621.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED.  REPRESENTATIVES OF THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE FITTINGS ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THEY FOUND THAT THE GASKET UNDERNEATH THE RUPTURE DISK HAD BUBBLED DUE TO CORROSION AND WAS ALLOWING VAPORS TO SEEP PAST THE RUPTURE DISK ASSEMBLY.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVES REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE GASKET AND INSTALLED A NEW RUPTURE DISK.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND CLOSURES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SEALED AND IN GOOD CONDITION. THERE WAS A MISCOMMUNICATION BETWEEN THE OPERATOR AND THE CTL DRIVER AS TO THE CONNECTION OF THE AIR LINE AND THE PRESSURE BEING USED TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT.  THE CARGO TANK WAS OVER PRESSURIZED AND THIS CAUSE THE VENT TO OPEN CAUSING A SOME AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASE FROM THE VENT.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS COUNSELED ON THE IMPORTANCE'S OF COMMUNICATIONS BETWEEN PLANT OPERATOR.  THE DRIVER SPENT 1 DAY IN RE-TRAINING WITH A CERTIFIED DRIVER TRAINER.  PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND THE VENT WAS REPAIRED.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT DOCKWORKER FOUND A PALLET OF BOXES THAT WAS BEING CRUSHED BY THE FREIGHT THAT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF IT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IN ONE OF THE BOXES THERE WERE TWO POLY JUGS LEAKING FROM THE SCREW ON CAPS AS A RESULT OF BEING CRUSHED. THE TWO DAMAGED JUGS WERE REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER, SPILLED MATERIAL EVAPORATED, AND BALANCE OF SHIPMENT WAS SENT TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

WHEN DOCKWORKER WENT TO UNLOAD FREIGHT FROM TRAILER HE DISCOVERED TWO DRUMS THAT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY FORKBLADES WHEN THE ORIGIN LOADER PLACED FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER BEHIND THEM. DAMAGED DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINERS ALONG WITH ABSORBENT AND NEUTRALIZER USED TO CLEAN UP SPILLED MATERIAL. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DUNNAGE WAS USED TO PROTECT THE FREIGHT AND IF FORKLIFT OPERATOR PAID ATTENTION TO THE CLEARANCES OF HIS FORKBLADES.

WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER DOCKWORKER NOTICED THE FLOOR WAS WET. AFTER HE REMOVED SOME FREIGHT HE NOTICED A BOX HAD BEEN CRUSHED IN BETWEEN TWO PALLETS.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A POLY JUG INSIDE THE BOX HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND WAS SLIGHTLY LEAKING.  POLY JUG WAS REMOVED FROM BOX AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT.  BALANCED OF SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT.

column168: TANK TRUCK DEPARTED THE STATE COLLEGE BULK PLANT AROUND 4:30AM WITH APPROX. 1235 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL ENROUTE TO A ROAD CONSTRUCTION SITE.  ABOUT 1 MILE FROM THE PLANT, A SUPPLY LINE SEPARATED AT A COUPLING SPREADING A 3 FT WIDE STRIP OF OIL FROM WADDLE RD, NORTH OF STATE RT 322 FOR 4 MILES TO THE JOB SITE AT SKYTOP.  THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FOR 12 HOURS DURING CLEAN-UP.  TO CLEAN UP THE ROAD SURFACE, 40 TONS OF LIME DUST WAS LAID DOWN & SWEPT UP, FOLLOWED BY ANOTHER 4 TONS OF OIL DRY ABSORBENT. SEVERAL TRUCK LOADS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA WHERE THE TRUCK STOPPED. THE REMAINING FUEL OIL WAS PUMPED OFF THE TRUCK & THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO A CERTIFIED REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION & REATTACHMENT OF THE RUPTURED LINE.  235 TONS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE AND SHIPPED TO ONYX GREENTREE LANDFILL, LLC, 635 TOBY RD, KERSEY, PA 15846. COPIES OF MANIFESTS ARE ATTACHED.

IN VICKERY, OHIO WHEN HE BECAME AWARE OF THE RELEASE AND DECIDED TO DRIVE DIRECTLY TO OUR DAYTON FACILITY DUE TO ITS PROXIMITY (5-10 MILES).  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE DAYTON FACILITY PERSONNEL FOUND ONE TOTE THAT HAD APPARENTLY LEAKED FROM THE VALVE.  THIS SPECIFIC TOTE HAD JUST BEEN RE-CERTIFIED IN JUNE OF 2003.  AFTER IMMEDIATE REVIEW OF THE SPECIFIC WASTE CODES THAT APPLIED TO THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND ANALYSIS THAT WAS PERFORMED ON THE WASTE REMAINING IN THE TOTE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT AN RQ WAS NOT RELEASED DURING TRANSPORTATION, BUT APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS RELEASED.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN PROVIDED TO RESPONSIBLE INDIVIDUALS REGARDING EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES FOR SPILLS DURING TRANSPORTATION.

AT CSX DAVID YARD FACILITY IN LELAND, NORTH CAROLINA AN EMPLOYEE OBSERVED TANK CAR GPPX 29196 (LOAD - METHANOL) WITH A CONTINUOUS LEAK FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CSX TERMINAL MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE YARD EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE SHIPPER, COLONIAL TERMINALS WAS CONTACTED. COLONIAL TERMINALS CONTRACTED HIGH RISE SERVICES AND RESCAR TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE RAIL CAR.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM HIGH RISE FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE 2-INCH LIQUID LINE EDUCTION VALVE.  IT APPEARS THAT THE OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE WAS STRUCK BY THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER (BREAD BASKET) WHEN IT WAS PLACED IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  THIS ACTION CAUSED THE VALVE TO SLIGHTLY OPEN.  IN ADDITION, THE LIQUID LINE CLOSURE PLUG WAS FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FLOW OUT OF THE VALVE AND AROUND THE PLUG.  HIGH RISE PERSONNEL CLOSED THE VALVE, REMOVED THE CLOSURE PLUG, WRAPPED THE PLUG WITH TEFLON TAPE, THEN REPLACED THE PLUG AND TIGHTENED IT WITH A WRENCH.  THE LEAK SUBSIDED AND THE RAIL CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF TRAIN Q61416 AT CSXT'S MAXWELL YARD IN GREENWOOD, SC WHEN NLTX5051, LOAD VINYL ACETATE, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR OF VAPORS.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT OF THE TRAIN IN THE YARD.  UNION CARBIDE (DOW) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA CHEMTREC.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING VAPORS FROM A DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO RESEAT THE VALVE HOWEVER IT CONTINUED TO LEAK VAPORS. UNION CARBIDE WAS ADVISED THAT THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED.  THEY RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WHO REMOVED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND INSTALLED A 3-INCH PLUG.  THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED; THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

ECUX 374061, LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SPLASH LEAK FROM THE TOP IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN GRAND RAPIDS, MI.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER, EXXON MOBIL CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  EXXON MOBIL AUTHORIZED CSXT TO CALL AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE GASKET ON THE FLANGE OF THE 2-INCH LIQUID EDUCTION LINE.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

GATX 57615, LOAD HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WAS SET OUT OF TRAIN, F75325, IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN AUGUSTA, GA, DUE TO THE CREW OBSERVING VAPORS AT THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER, VULCAN CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  VULCAN SENT AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CHECK THE CAR AND MAKE REPAIRS.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS RUPTURED.  THE CONTRACTOR INSTALLED A NEW 165LB FRANGIBLE DISK AND SECURED THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN PARKERSBURG, WV, REPORTED THAT GATX62624, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WAS VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER, TETRA CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION AND RESPONDED A TECHNICIAN TO INSPECT THE CAR. TETRA CHEMICAL'S REPRESENTATIVE REPORTED THAT THE RUBBER GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OF THE GRAPHITE FRANGIBLE DISK WAS DEFORMED (PUCKERED) PREVENTING A VAPOR TIGHT SEAL AND ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE AROUND THE GASKET.  HE REPLACED THE FRANGIBLE DISK WITH A NEW DISK WITH A NEW DISK AND SECURED THE CAR.  THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED.  IN FOLLOW UP WITH TETRA CHEMICAL THEY ADVISED THAT THEY HAVE HAD A PROBLEM WITH DEFORMED RUBBER GASKETS ON THE BOTTOM OF FRANGIBLE DISKS TERTA CHEMICAL HAS INSTALLED A NEW TEFLON SURGE PROTECTORS IN THEIR CARS THAT PROVIDE A WIDER CONTACT SURFACE THAN THE DISK GASKET ALONE TO ENSURE A VAPOR TIGHT SEAL.

JR SIMPLOT'S REPRESENTATIVE VONITA REAVIS APPLIED AND WAS GRANTED A MOVEMENT EXEMPTION (FRA-0309217) FROM THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION.  THE RAIL CAR IS BEING SENT TO UNION TANK CAR IN MUSCATINE, IOWA FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:10 AM (PST), A BP TANKER TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON THE 710 FREEWAY BETWEEN THE FIRESTONE AND FLORENCE EXITS IN THE CITY OF BELL GARDENS IN THE LOS ANGELES AREA THAT RESULTED IN THE FATALITY OF OUT DRIVER. BP DRIVER TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON THE 710 FREEWAY AFTER THE VINVALE TERMINAL. APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE FROM THE TERMINAL, HE CAME UPON A DISABLED ABANDON VEHICLE WITH NO LIGHTS ON THAT WERE LEFT IN THE #4 LANE. THE BP DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID THE ABANDON CAR CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE TRUCK AND RESULTED IN A ROLL OVER OF BOTH THE TRUCK AND TRAILER, WHICH CAUGHT ON FIRE. NO OTHER VEHICLES OR INJURIES WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. THE ARCO-BRANDED TANKER WAS CARRYING 9,001 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. TERMINAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 AM AND ARRIVED ON SCENE BY 3:00 AM TO DIRECT CLEAN UP EFFORTS AND TO ASSIST FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ON FIRE FIGHTING OPERATIONS. APPROXIMATELY 150 RESIDENTS OF A NEARBY APARTMENT COMPLEX WERE EVACUATED AS THE RESULT OF THE FIRE. RESIDUAL FUEL LEFT IN THE TANKER WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE BY MEANS OF VACUUM TRUCKS WITH APPROXIMATELY 6,200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE RECOVERED. OF THE 28,00 GALLONS OF GASOLINE, WHICH WAS NOT RECOVERED, THE MAJORITY WAS LOST AS THE RESULT OF THE FIRE. A CORPORATE ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION IS IN PROGRESS.

LOCAL POLICE OFFICER STOPPED CARRIER VEHICLE BECAUSE HE SMELLED A CHEMICAL SMELL.  OFFICER CLOSED DOWN HWY 146 AND BEGAN INSPECTING VEHICLE AND COULD FIND NO LEAK.  AFTER MORE THAn ONE HOUR A TEXAS DPS OFFICER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND OPENED THE ROADWAY IMMEDIATELY AND ESCORTED THE CARRIER VEHICLE BACK TO THE SHIPPER LOCATION.  CARRIER MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL INSPECTED VEHICLE.  ALL VENTING DEVICES, DOME LID AND WASH OUT CAPS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND IN PROPER WORKING ORDER.  VACUUM DEVICE HAD A SCRATCH OR NICK ON THE SEAT WHICH WAS BUFFED OUT AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.  CARRIER VEHICLE CONTINUED ON TRIP WITH OUT FURTHER INCIDENT. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT SHIPPER MAY HAVE RELEASED A VERY SMALL AMOUNT-DROPS-AROUND THE DOME AREA DURING LOADING.  AFTER TEXAS DPS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND TOOK OVER INCIDENT LOCAL OFFICER DECIDED TO SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION.  NO ONE ELSE AT THE SCENE REQUIRED MEDICAL ATTENTION.

THE DRIVER WAS IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHEN THE PLANT EXPERIENCED A POWER OUTAGE, THE PUMP RUNS OFF ELECTRIC POWER AND DID NOT HAVE ANY OTHER SOURCE OF POWER TO RUN ON. THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM AND LIGHT WAS GOING OFF WHEN THIS OCCURRED. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND FOUND A PLANT OPERATOR TO FIND OUT WHAT HE WAS GOING TO BE ABLE TO DO. THE PLANT OPERATOR TOLD THE DRIVER THAT THE ENTIRE PLANT WAS EXPERIENCING AN OUTAGE AND IT WOULD BE A FEW MINUTES UNTIL HE COULD HELP HIM. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED BACK TO HIS UNIT AND DECIDED TO FINISH UNLOADING. PRODUCT RAN OUT THE BACK SIDE OF THE PIT INTO THE PLANT CONTAINMENT. CTL SENT IN  A CREW TO CLEAN UP THE HARDEN SULFUR. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED DUE TO PLANT AND COMPANY POLICY VIOLATIONS.

WHILE LOADING A 55 GALLON DRUM OF THE ABOVE CHEMICAL, THE DRUM MADE CONTACT WITH A PROTRUSION OF METAL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BARREL CAUSING A LEAK. I ISOLATED THE SPILL TO ENSURE THE RELEASE WOULD NOT TRAVEL ANY FURTHER. IDENTIFICATION OF THE PRODUCT CAME NEXT MAKING SURE OF THE PACKING GROUP AND WHAT IMMEDIATE ACTIONS WERE NEEDED.  I THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AT 2100 TO INFORM THEM OF THE SPILL AND TO RECEIVE FURTHER DIRECTIONS. ERTS CALLED ME BACK AT 2125 AND ADVISED THE SPILL WOULD BE SAFE FOR ME TO CLEAN UP. THE RELEASE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED WITH AMPHOMAG AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE METAL PROTRUSION WILL BE FIXED IMMEDIATELY TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER INCIDENT.

THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF LIQUID HYDROGEN TO BE DELIVERED TO VARIOUS CUSTOMER LOCATIONS FOR DELIVERY. DURING THE EARLY MORNING HOURS OF SEPTEMBER 15, 2003, WHILE DRIVING NORTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 5, HE NOTICED A WHITE VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER AND AN INCREASE IN THE INTERNAL VAPOR PRESSURE GAUGE. THE DRIVER THEN MADE THE DECISION TO EXIT I-5 AT THE FIRST AVAILABLE OPPORTUNITY, WHICH WAS HIGHWAY 126. THIS EXIT APPEARED TO BE A LOW VOLUME TRAFFIC AREA AT 5:30 IN THE MORNING, HOWEVER, IT IS THE MAIN ROAD CONNECTING SPRINGFIELD, OR WITH EUGENE, OR. BECAUSE OF THE DRIVERS TRAINING IN THE HANDLING OF LIQUID HYDROGEN, HE KNEW THERE WAS A PROBLEM, AND HE NEEDED TO POSITION HI TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT WHERE IT WOULD CAUSE THE LEAST AMOUNT OF DANGER TO THE MOTORING PUBLIC. THE HYDROGEN TRAILER HAD EXPERIENCED AN UNEXPLAINED LOSS OF VACUUM BETWEEN THE INNER VESSEL AND OUTER VESSEL. WHEN THIS OCCURS, THE LIQUID PRODUCT BEGINS TO VAPORIZE AND THE VAPOR PRESSURE OF THE PRODUCT RISES TO A POINT WHERE THE SAFETY DEVICES WILL RELIEVE ALL EXCESS PRESSURE TO THE ATMOSPHERE. WITH THE COMPLETE LOSS OF VACUUM, THE ENTIRE LOAD OF LIQUID PRODUCT HAD TO BE VENTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. WITH THE HELP OF LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, THE SURROUNDING AREAS WERE ASKED TO VOLUNTARILY EVACUATE UNTIL THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL. ONCE THE PRESSURE WAS AT A CONTROLLABLE LEVEL, THE UNIT WAS MOVED FROM THE ROADWAY AND TAKEN TO A SAFER LOCATION FOR FURTHER EVALUATION. THE TRAILER WAS EVENTUALLY TRANSPORTED TO THE ORIGINAL MANUFACTURER FOR A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO PROPERTY DAMAGE, AND NO SPILL. THERE WAS HOWEVER, A VAPOR (GAS) DISPERSION AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. ALL TERMINALS WERE NOTIFIED OF THIS EVENT, AND IT WILL BE DISCUSSED IN THE MONTHLY SAFETY MEETINGS.

THERE HAVE NO HOURS OF SERVICE VIOLATIONS IDENTIFIED, NOR WERE THERE ANY MECHANICAL FAILURES FOUND DURING THE INVESTIGATION.  THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE THE DRIVER FAILED TO COMMUNICATE HIS LACK OF PROPER REST DURING HIS OFF-DUTY TIME. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 15, 2003, A DRIVER FROM QUALITY CARRIERS WAS LOADING HIS CARGO TANK WITH SPENT SULFURIC ACID AT THE COASTAL REFINERY.  THE DRIVER APPARENTLY OVER-LOADED THE TRUCK.  THE TRUCK IS TOP-LOADED AND THE DRIVER APPARENTLY OPENED THE FILL VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE TRUCK RACK AND THEN CAME DOWN TO GROUND LEVEL FOR A TIME AND WAS NOT ABLE TO GET BACK UP ON THE RACK IN TIME TO STOP THE FOLLOW WHEN HE NOTICED THE OVERFILL OF HIS TRUCK.  OF THE 40 GALLONS THAT SPILLED, ABOUT 15 GALLONS GOT OUT OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT ONTO SURROUNDING SOIL.  REFINERY CLEANUP CONTRACTORS NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED ACID WITH SODA ASH.  THE NEUTRALIZED LIQUID WAS VACUUMED UP AND DELIVERED TO THE REFINERY WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT.  TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVERS WHO PICK UP ACID FROM THE REFINERY WERE GIVEN A SAFETY TALK ABOUT PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES AT THE QC TERMINAL ON SEPT. 20, 2003.

column168: RECEIVED A CALL FROM DELAWARE COUNTY REPORTING AN OVERTURNED TANKER, LEAKING FUEL OIL ON SPRAUL ROAD JUST PASS CARDINAL O'HARE HIGH SCHOOL.  A CREW WAS DISPATCHED.  INITIAL REPORTS WERE GIVEN THAT APPROXIMATELY 1,000 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL HAD BEEN RELEASED.  DURING THE RESPONSE FOLLOW-UP REPORTS WERE RECEIVED STATING THAT THE INITIAL RELEASE WAS SEVERELY OVER ESTIMATED.  UPON ARRIVAL AN ASSESSMENT WAS MADE.  APPROXIMATELY 4-GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL WERE SPILLED AND CONTAINED AT THE FRONT OF THE TRUCK. APPROXIMATELY 5-GALLONS OF FUEL OIL HAD LEAKED FROM THE REAR DOME.  NO PUNCTURES OR LEAKS WERE EVIDENT FROM THE SKIN OF THE TANK.  THE REAR DOME WAS STILL LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON EVERY FIFTEEN MINUTES.  THIS LEAK WAS SEALED WITH GAP SEAL AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD PLACED OIL STRATEGICALLY TO PREVENT FURTHER SPREAD OF FUEL AND OIL.  ACCORDING TO EMERGENCY RESPONDERS THE TANKER WAS PROCEEDING EAST ON SPRAUL ROAD WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND BEGAN TO SKID IN THE WESTBOUND LANES.  THE TRUCK HIT ONE CAR AND BEGAN TO ROLL.  THE TRUCK THEN ROLLED OVER A SECOND  CAR ENTRAPPING A MAN AND HIS GRANDDAUGHTER.  THE TANKER CAME TO REST JUST PAST THE SECOND CAR.  FOLLOWING THE ARRIVAL OF AN OFF-LOAD TANKER THE OVERTURNED TANK WAS DRILLED AND ALL PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED.  ONCE LEVELS HAD BEEN LOWERED BELOW THE DOMES PRODUCT REMOVAL WAS DONE THROUGH THE DOMES.  DURING PRODUCT REMOVAL OIL DRY WAS PLACED OVER ALL SPILLED FLUIDS AND CLEAN UP BEGAN.  ONCE THE OFFLOAD WAS COMPLETED THE TRUCK WAS UPRIGHTED BY DEAN KEYS TOWING AND ALL REMAINING CLEAN-UP WAS CONCLUDED.  TWO DRUMS OF WASTE WERE GENERATED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  ALL PERSONNEL SECURED FROM THE SITE, RETURNED TO THE SHOP, RESTORED EQUIPMENT, AND RESTOCKED EXPENDABLES.  SIX BAGS OF OIL DRY, ONE BAIL OF 5" BOOM, AND ONE BAIL OF OIL PADS WERE PROVIDED TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DUE TO USAGE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM ON 9/23/03, A LOW SPEED (15 MPH) COLLISION INVOLVING TWO TANKER TRUCKS (CARGO TANKS) OCCURRED WITHIN THE TERMINAL YARD AT THE GLOBAL PETROLEUM CORP, LOADING RACK LOCATED ON 140 LEE BURBANK HIGHWAY REVERE MA.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AS ONE TANKER TRUCK WAS BACKING OUT OF BAY #11 WITH AN ANOTHER TANKER TRUCK DRIVING ALONG THE LOADING RACK. THE COLLISION SHEARED OFF ONE OF THE TANK COMPARTMENTS MANIFOLD VALVE AND DREAD FUEL BEGAN LEAKING OUT OF THE COMPARTMENT ONTO THE PAVED SURFACE. YARD PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY SEALED THE MANIFOLD PIPE, HOWEVER A 1200 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  CLEAN HARBOR WAS RETAINED AS THE 'CLEAN UP' CONTRACTOR. WHITMORE AND WAS ADVISED THE LOCATION OF THE TANKCAR WAS 7005 S KYRENE RD. TEMPE AZ.  MR JACKSON REQUESTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, STATE, AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE.  MR. WHITMORE ADVISED ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHT AND THE GASKET WERE DISPLACED, DEFECTIVE AND BULGING CAUSING VAPORS TO BE RELEASED. CONSIGNEE, ROMIC ENVIRONMENTAL AT CHANDLER, AZ. ON WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 10, 2003 AT 1550 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, TOBY TREVETT WAS NOTIFIED BY IMS CHIEF CLERK WAYNE STETMAN THAT ISO TANK TRLU 23790 WAS LEAKING ON PAD G IN THE AVONDALE YARD.  SAHM TREVETT RESPONDED.  UPON HIS ARRIVAL, SAHM TREVETT MET WITH BILL MOSS, THE PAC RAIL SERVICES MANAGER IN AVONDALE, LA. AND DAVID GARLAND, CHASSIS REPAIRMEN FOR AVONDALE CONTAINER SERVICE.  MR. GARLAND ADVISED THAT WHILE HE WAS REPAIRING A CHASSIS IN THE VICINITY OF PAD G, JUST SHORTLY AFTER IT STARTED TO RAIN, HIS EYES STARTED TO BURN AND HE FELT AN IRRITATION TO HIS SKIN ON HIS FACE.  HE ADVISED THAT HE THEN OBSERVED A LIGHT YELLOW SUBSTANCE FORM IN THE BOTTOM OF A MUD PUDDLE ON THE INTERMODAL PAD G, IN FRONT OF THE ISO TANK TRLU 23790 AND TWO OTHER MID PUDDLES TO THE RIGHT AND THE LEFT OF THE TANK.  MR. GARLAND FURTHER ADVISED THAT, HE REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO MR. MOSS WHO CAME TO THE LOCATION AND OBSERVED SAME AND FELT EYE IRRITATION AND A BURNING SENSATION TO HIS FACE.  HE ADVISED THAT THEY GOT ABSORBENT PADS TO PUT DOWN ON THE GROUND TO STOP THE SPREAD OF THE CHEMICAL.  SAHM TREVETT FELT THE SAME SENSATION.  A TWO HUNDRED SQUARE FOOT AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED.  SAHM TREVETT CONTRACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION CO. TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO CONTACTED.  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION CO. RESPONSE PERSONNEL, WEARING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, INSPECTED THE TANK AND DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY THREE TO FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT WHICH WAS IN A CRYSTALLINE SOLID FORM HAD BEEN SPILLED INTO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THE TOP OF THE TANK AND IT HAD NOT BEEN CLEANED OFF.  AS THE TEMPERATURE ROSE TO NINETY DEGREES AND THE RAIN STARTED THE SOLID CHANGED TO A LIQUID, AND RAN FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR TO THE GROUND.  THIS CAUSED THE MUD PUDDLES TO DISCOLOR.  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION CO. CLEANED UP THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND CLEANED UP THE MUD PUDDLES WITH A PUMP AND PLACED THE CONTENTS INTO LARGE PLASTIC DRUMS.  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION CO. HANDLED DISPOSAL OF THE DRUMS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS A UPRR CLERK THAT WAS NOT ON THE SCENE, BUT SITTING IN THE UPRR INTERMODAL OFFICE IN AVONDALE WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 500 FEET AWAY FROM THE INCIDENT COMPLAINED THAT HE FELT VERY BAD AND REQUESTED THAT HE BE TAKEN TO A HOSPITAL.  HE WAS TAKEN TO WEST JEFFERSON HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT.

column168: NCR-700791, INDIANA: IN-2003-09-211 THE INCIDENT OCCURRED THURSDAY NIGHT, SEPTEMBER 25 AT AROUND 9:45 PM AT THE ROYSTER-CLARK WAREHOUSE LOCATED ON HARLAN DRIVE IN TERRE-HAUTE INDIANA. THIEVES STEALING AMMONIA WERE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERING AMMONIA FROM A 1450 GALLON NURSE TANK INTO A SMALL PROPANE BOTTLE. A GARDEN HOSE WAS BEING USED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT. FOR SOME REASON THE THIEVES LEFT THE SCENE AND LEFT THE VALVES OPEN ON THE TANKS CAUSING ABOUT 310 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO BE RELEASED FROM THE TANKS INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. SOMEONE REPORTED THE THEFT AND RELEASE IN PROGRESS TO AUTHORITIES. THE HONEY CREEK FIRE DEPARTMENT SET UP A WATER FOG AT THE SCENE, KNOCKED DOWN THE AMMONIA CLOUD, AND WENT IN AND CLOSED THE TANK VALVES. THE VALVE ON THE PROPANE TANK WOULD NOT CLOSE COMPLETELY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MAINTAINED THE WATER FOG ON THE TANK AND ALLOWED THE AMMONIA IN THE PROPANE TANK TO DISSIPATE TO THE ATMOSPHERE. ABOUT 2600 GALLONS OF WATER WERE USED TO CONTROL THE RELEASE. DURING THE RELEASE, HARLAN DRIVE AND US HIGHWAY 41 WERE CLOSED DOWN FOR ABOUT AN HOUR. AS A PRECAUTION, RESIDENTS OF ONE DWELLING JUST TO THE SOUTH WEST OF THE ROYSTER-CLARK LOCATION EVACUATED FOR ABOUT AN HOUR. THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED.IDEM OFFICIALS WERE AT THE SCENE ON FRIDAY SEPTEMBER 26 TO EVALUATE THE SITE. AT THAT TIME IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE WATER USED TO CONTROL THE AMMONIA CLOUD HAD POOLED IN AREAS OF THE PROPERTY. THE WATER WAS TESTED AND DETERMINED TO CONTAIN IN EXCESS OF 8 PPM AMMONIA NITROGEN. CLEAN UP OPERATIONS WERE STARTED TO RECOVER THE WATER AND TO GET THE AMMONIA NITROGEN LEVELS DOWN TO 4 PPM OR LESS. A BACKHOE WAS BROUGHT IN AND USED TO DIG 5 COLLECTION PITS AND TO BUILD A DAM IN A DRAINAGE DITCH. FIFTEEN ROYSTER-CLARK ASSOCIATED RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO AID IN THE CLEANUP OPERATIONS. FOUR TANKER TRUCKS, TWO NURSE TANKS, AND THREE PUMPS WERE USED IN THE CLEANUP. TWO THOUSAND GALLONS OF CLEAN WATER WERE USED BY ROYSTER-CLARK ASSOCIATES TO FLUSH THE AREA. THE HONEY CREEK FIRE DEPARTMENT SENT A PUMPER AND TWO MEN TO AID THE THE WASHDOWN. THE FLUSHING AND RECOVERY OPERATION CONTINUED INTO FRIDAY NIGHT UNTIL HEAVY RAINS FELL. ABOUT 2.1 INCHES OF RAN FELL ON THE AREA. ON SATURDAY MORNING SEPT. 27, THE CLEANUP OPERATION RESUMED. THE WATER IN THE COLLECTION PITS AND DITCH CHECKED FROM 2 PPM TO 4 PPM. THE WATER WAS PUMPED FROM THE PITS AND DITCH. THE PITS AND THE DITCH WERE LEFT OPEN AND MONITORED. ON WEDNESDAY OCTOBER 1ST THE WATER IN THE PITS AND THE DITCH CHECKED 2 TO 3.5 PPM AMMONIA NITROGEN. THE WATER WAS PUMPED OUT AND THE PITS WERE CLOSED. IN ALL ABOUT 11,400 GALLONS OF WATER WERE RECOVERED FROM THE DITCH AND PITS. THE WATER IS BEING STORED ON ROYSTER-CLARK EQUIPMENT AND WILL BE LAND APPLIED AS SOON AS SOIL MOISTURE CONDITIONS ALLOW.

column168: WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL TO OVER-NITE TRANSPORTATION IN CUMBERLAND, MD; SEL-LO OIL, INC. SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS.  AFTER POSITIONING HIS TRUCK AND ARRANGING THE UNLOADING EQUIPMENT BRIAN HOLLERN BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE DIESEL INTO THEIR 10,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND TANK. MORE THAN HALF WAY THROUGH THE UNLOADING PROCESS A SEVERE RAIN STORM CAME THROUGH THE AREA.  IT SOON LEFT STANDING WATER THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE PARKING LOT, AND BRIAN ATTEMPTED TO KEEP THE TANK UNLOADING WELL CLEAR OF WATER.  SOMETIME DURING THE STORM THE UNLOADING DROP HEAD BECAME DISCONNECTED FROM THE COLLAR ON THE TOP OF THEIR TANK, THE WEATHER WAS SO SEVERE THAT IT WENT UNDETECTED FOR AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF TIME.  THE FUEL GOT DISPURSED BY THE INCREASING AMOUNT OF GROUND WATER.

column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF CONTAINER MOLU 270501 ONTO THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN SPACE YELLOW 136 AT THE ICTF FACILITY.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  UPON INSPECTION, NOTED A SMALL POOL OF PRODUCT UNDER THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DECK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THEY HAD ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT THE LISTED SHIPPER, MITSUI OSK LINES, HOWEVER, THE SHIPPER IS NOT REGISTERED WITH CHEMTREC.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS FOR INSPECTION, FOUND THE LADING CONSISTED OF 75 METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLED STACKED.  BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE, BUT WAS NOT STANDARD PER THE AAR BOE PAMPHLET 6C.  AS THE LEAKING PRODUCT HAD SUBSIDED IT WAS DECIDED TO WORK THE LOAD THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  THE SHIPPER, LIBRIZOL, WAS CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING MORNING AND ADVISED OF THE LEAKING CONDITION, WHICH WOULD REQUIRE THE DRUMS TO BE REMOVED IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKER.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO PERFORM THE TRANSLOAD.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE SIDE WALL, APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES ABOVE THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE PUNCTURE APPEARS TO BE FROM A FORK LIFT OPERATED DRUM GRAPPLER, AS THERE WERE NO PROTRUSIONS FROM ANY OF THE SURROUNDING DRUMS.  SUSPECT THE PUNCTURE OCCURRED WHILE THE DRUMS WERE BEING LOADED AT THE POINT OF ORIGIN.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT FOR RETURN SHIPMENT TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.

column168: AT 0520HRS ON 9-14-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED OF A FOUR CAR DERAILMENT IN THE LAKE CHARLES YARD; LAKE CHARLES, LA.  ALL CARS WERE UPRIGHT, WITH CAR GATX12761 REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WITH FLOW OF PRODUCT SLIGHTLY LARGER THAN THE SIZE OF A PENCIL.  CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO THE LEG OF THE VALVE BEING SHEERED OFF BY THE TRUCK ASSEMBLY AS IT SLIDE ALONG THE BOTTOM SIDE OF THE CAR DURING THE DERAILMENT.  UPON BEING NOTIFIED, MGR LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER CONTACT VIA CHEMTREC AND APPROPRIATE STATE NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE.    AT APPROXIMATELY 0550HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO BILL BURKET, BAYER CORP. EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGER.  HE INDICATED THAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL WOULD BE ENROUTE TO ASSIST.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0900HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO MICHELLE GOTZMANN, SCHENECTADY INTERNATIONAL, SR RAIL LOGISTICS ANALYST ADVISING HER OF THE DERAILMENT.  WHILE ENROUTE, MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED THAT THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM TANK CAR GATX 12761 HAD BEEN STOPPED BY THE LAKE CHARLES FIRE DEPT BY CLOSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE VIA THE OPERATING HANDLE. ON ARRIVAL AT SCENE MGR LERCH INSPECTED ALL CARS INVOLVED NOTING MINOR TO MODERATE DAMAGE TO THE CARS.  ON ARRIVAL OF PAT BAKER RERAILING CREWS, ALL CARS WERE RERAILED WITH CAR GATX 12761 LATER MOVED TO THE WYE FOR TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO TANK TRUCKS BY HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  AT 1600HRS TRANSFER ACTIVITIES BEGAN AND WERE COMPLETED AT 0555HRS ON 9-15-03. PRODUCT TO BE TRANSPORTED BACK TO POINT OF ORIGIN, BAYER CORPORATION; BAYTOWN, TX. THE AFFECTED AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH THE APPLICATION OF 17 GALLONS OF MURIATIC ACID.  THE APPLICATION WAS DONE UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF LOUISIANA STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, RON CADY.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.  ON 9-18-03 TANK CAR GATX 12761 WAS CLEANED AND PURGED BY HULCHER SERVICES AND RELEASED FOR MECHANICAL REPAIRS.

RONNY LLOYD, CAR FOREMAN, ADVISED YARD PERSONNEL REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 83148 WAS LEAKING A STEADY STREAM FROM A LOWER VALVE OF THE TANKCAR ON TRACK 60 IN THE KIRBY YARD IN KIRBY, TX MR. LLOYD STATED THE RAILCAR WAS ENTRAINED ON TRAIN QHOWC 29. PAUL PERSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER PERSON ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. THE CAP WAS RESEALED AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED.

column168: ON 09/22/2003 CTS MGR M. KELLY WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF A DERAILMENT IN NEY YARD INVOLVING A OPEN TOP HOPPER CAR CONTAINING A REGULATED MATERIAL. KELLY RESPONDED TO THE DERAILMENT SITE WHERE HE FOUND MP 588949 DERAILED WITH APPROXIMATELY ONE THIRD OF IT'S LOAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  KELLY HAD A CONTRACTOR REMOVE THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND AT A LATER DATE THE CONTENTS REMAINING IN THE RAILCAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER HOPPER.
